<DOC><DOCNO> AP880523-0243 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1405EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Transplant-Glance Adv26   05-23 0370</FIRST><SECOND>BC-EXP--Transplant-Glance, Adv 26,0381</SECOND><NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Thursday, May 26, and Thereafter</NOTE><HEAD>Sketches of Transplant Law, Organizations</HEAD><HEAD>With BC-EXP--Transplant Rules</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are the law governing organ transplant, thetask force that grew out of it, and the network under contract tohelp implement it.</TEXT><BYLINE>National Organ Transplant Act</BYLINE><TEXT>   The National Organ Transplant Act was passed by Congress in 1984in response to the growing need for a national transplant systemand medical and ethical guidelines. It called for formation of aNational Task Force on Organ Transplantation and mandatedestablishment of a national Organ Procurement and TransplantationNetwork to be administered by a private group with oversight of theU.S. Department of Health and Human Services. It provided grants toorgan procurement groups to help increase their effectiveness andpromote organ donation. It also called for establishment of aregistry of recipients.</TEXT><BYLINE>National Task Force on Organ Transplantation</BYLINE><TEXT>   The National Task Force on Organ Transplantation is a 25-memberpanel that made 70 recommendations to Congress and to the secretaryof Health and Human Services in 1986. The panel of doctors andexperts, which no longer exists, recommended:   _That hearts and livers go to Americans whenever possible andthat foreigners make up no more than 10 percent of the total kidneyrecipients at any transplant center.   _A ban on the exportation of donor organs, except when noappropriate recipients can be found in the United States.   _That all states pass laws under which hospitals would berequired to approach families about the possibility of organdonation.   _That a federal entity be established for organ transplantation.That entity is the Division of Organ Transplantation, part of theU.S. Department of Health and Human Services.</TEXT><BYLINE>United Network for Organ Sharing</BYLINE><TEXT>   UNOS is a non-profit organization based in Richmond, Va., thatwas given a federal contract in 1986 to set up the national OrganProcurement and Transplantation Network, which links by computerall U.S. transplant centers, organ procurement agencies andtissue-typing laboratories. Membership is mandatory in order forthese institutions to receive federal Medicare reimbursements.   UNOS' 31-member board in 1987 approved mandatory guidelines forallocation of donated organs.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for May 26</NOTE></DOC>